<article id="post-3415" class="post-3415 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-children category-general tag-books tag-writing">
	<header class="entry-header">
		
		<h2 class="entry-title"><a href="http://geoff.wp/2014/04/so-i-wrote-a-book/" rel="bookmark">So, I wrote a book&#8230;</a></h2>	</header><!-- .entry-header -->

	
	
	<div class="entry-content">
		<p>I like writing. [Insert world&#8217;s largest &#8216;Well, DUH!&#8217; here.] And while I&#8217;ve been content to write a blog &#8212; great practice for any writer, if you ask me &#8212; it&#8217;s just not the same as when you write for someone else.<br />
Which I have. I&#8217;ve been fortunate enough to write a few things (articles, not long ones) for which I&#8217;ve been paid, and presumably read. That&#8217;s a bit more rewarding than merely standing on a soapbox and yelling into The Void. But even that isn&#8217;t quite enough.<br />
I think that&#8217;s what I wanted to write a book. But not the one I just published.<br />
 <a href="http://geoff.wp/2014/04/so-i-wrote-a-book/#more-3415" class="more-link">Continue reading<span class="screen-reader-text"> &#8220;So, I wrote a book&#8230;&#8221;</span></a></p>
	</div><!-- .entry-content -->

